media_camera Manly's Steve Matai and Brett Stewart to retire. Pic Brett Costello Manly Sea Eagles stars Brett Stewart and Steve Matai to retire Andrew Prentice, Manly Daily February 10, 2017 5:32pm Zorba column: Top spots on the line Amone is a bolt from the blue and gold
DUAL premiership winning Sea Eagles stars Brett Stewart and Steve Matai will not don the maroon and white again.
media_camera Manly Sea Eagles centre Steve Matai Picture: Braden Fastier NRL/ Rugby League
The pair, who won NRL titles in 2008 and 2011, have battled ongoing knee and neck injuries respectively since last season.
Stewart and Matai have not been able to do any pre-season training following surgery and as a result the curtain has finally closed on their illustrious careers.
On Friday afternoon, Manly revealed they are seeking medical retirement clearances from the NRL, the Rugby League Players Association (RLPA) and the players’ managers George Mimis (Stewart) and Gavin Orr (Matai) to give them a dignified and respectful exit from their brilliant careers.
Club management also intend to give Stewart and Matai a fond farewell in front of their adoring fans at Lottoland, likely to be in round one against Parramatta on Sunday, March 5.
Stewart made his NRL debut for the Sea Eagles on July 6, 2003.
He quickly earnt the moniker the ‘Prince of Brookvale’ due to his remarkable ability to find the tryline on home soil.
Aside from his two NRL rings, the man they call Snake represented NSW in State of Origin on eight occasions, scoring five tries.
He also played for NSW Country, the Prime Minister’s XIII and the Kangaroos.
Matai, regarded as one of the heaviest hitters in the game, joined the club ahead of the 2005 campaign from Wynnum Manly in Queensland.
He donned the colours of New Zealand 10 times and with Jamie Lyon formed one of the game’s best centre partnerships.
